01:02:30,360 --> 01:02:36,840
too... If a endpoint [inaudible 01:02:34] all 
companies is a convergence on a set of four or  

603
01:02:36,840 --> 01:02:42,840
five people who can afford them, that just creates 
too much of a monoculture, I think, in thinking. 

604
01:02:44,360 --> 01:02:49,120
I like that Shopify is different. I think this 
is good. I think it's a terrible place to work  

605
01:02:49,120 --> 01:02:54,800
for many, many, many people. It's the best 
place in the world to work for some people.  

606
01:02:57,440 --> 01:03:03,680
That's so good. That's what we want, I think. 
We want more of this. We want people to be  

607
01:03:03,680 --> 01:03:09,200
able to window-shop for a place where they can 
be enormously successful, because the place's  

608
01:03:09,200 --> 01:03:22,120
set of beliefs just fits you like a glove.
100 years. We have very long-term plans. 100  

609
01:03:22,120 --> 01:03:30,680
years, you can't talk about this software product, 
but you can talk about the mission itself,  

610
01:03:30,680 --> 01:03:37,000
whatever things that will survive for 80 years 
that are left on this particular timeframe.  

611
01:03:38,520 --> 01:03:44,400
Entrepreneurship is just precious. Shopify exists, 
basically you make entrepreneurship more common.  

612
01:03:45,080 --> 01:03:50,800
That is the thing we wanted to cause in the world. 
We have had, I think, success doing this already,  

613
01:03:50,800 --> 01:03:59,400
but again, there's no speed limit and no stopping 
point for this. As I keep saying, the word's  

614
01:03:59,400 --> 01:04:06,080
unbelievably path dependent. And therefore, if we 
are part of a path, we can cause it to be more in  

615
01:04:06,080 --> 01:04:11,120
adherence to the things that we value and would 
like to see. This is the wonderful thing about  

616
01:04:11,120 --> 01:04:21,280
company building. They can have lasting impact.
We are making decisions based on all the things  

617
01:04:21,280 --> 01:04:29,800
that we can do. What are the things that will 
be most long-term valuable for the long-term  

618
01:04:29,800 --> 01:04:37,920
pursuits we are on, and how can we normalize 
entrepreneurship? It's a thing that's really  

619
01:04:37,920 --> 01:04:43,160
important to me, just because people don't 
spend enough time on it. It's all economics.  

620
01:04:43,160 --> 01:04:52,000
Our [inaudible 01:04:44] living entirely depends 
on businesses. We are all part and tag of an  

621
01:04:52,000 --> 01:04:59,000
environment that is extremely entrepreneurial 
and actually celebrates entrepreneurship as  

622
01:04:59,000 --> 01:05:04,680
a courageous act and a glorious act even.
But that's not true in most of the world. In fact,  

623
01:05:04,680 --> 01:05:12,800
most people never encounter anyone who engages 
in doing that. It's not something people see  

624
01:05:12,800 --> 01:05:17,920
as one of their options. I want us to make 
these choices. And I think the long-term  

625
01:05:17,920 --> 01:05:26,080
focus matters. It's also really powerful for 
decision making. And I know this is potentially  

626
01:05:26,080 --> 01:05:36,960
intuitive to most, but also rarely practiced. 
You've had a lot of people from Stripe on here.  

627
01:05:38,280 --> 01:05:44,880
Stripe and Shopify have had a very long-term 
partnership. Stripe and Shopify had potentially  

628
01:05:44,880 --> 01:05:53,160
the most valuable partnership, or at least one of 
the top ones in history, of technology, because  

629
01:05:53,680 --> 01:05:57,840
we were both very small companies and we decided, 
hey, let's work on an assumption that both of us  

630
01:05:57,840 --> 01:06:02,560
are going to win our markets, and work together. 
So, Stripe's [inaudible 01:06:02] for payments and  

631
01:06:02,560 --> 01:06:11,440
we're allowed a part of Stripe and so on.
When you're in a partnership like this,  

632
01:06:11,440 --> 01:06:17,200
you play basically iterated prisoner's dilemma. 
Every instance, every turn you can make a choice:  

633
01:06:17,200 --> 01:06:24,440
coordinate or defect, defecting if the other 
person collaborates, collaborator effect. If both  

634
01:06:24,440 --> 01:06:30,480
collaborate, everyone gets a point. If one defects 
and the other one collaborates, you get a lot of  

635
01:06:30,480 --> 01:06:39,920
points, all at one moment. Being a good partner in 
business is like this corporate marshmallow test  

636
01:06:39,920 --> 01:06:46,680
that companies tend to fail in a very funny way.
If you see the videos of kids doing actual actual  

637
01:06:46,680 --> 01:06:52,080
marshmallow tests, the smart ones actually turn 
the chair around, look away from the marshmallow,  

638
01:06:52,080 --> 01:06:57,760
and sit on their hands, and just go vibrating. 
Because they know it's the right thing to wait  

639
01:06:57,760 --> 01:07:01,760
for getting two marshmallows in the future, 
but man, if they just look at a marshmallow,  

640
01:07:01,760 --> 01:07:08,560
they'll just eat it. Most CEOs, most companies 
can't even successfully do that and just engage  

641
01:07:08,560 --> 01:07:14,440
in pulling future profits forward at a 
discount or even defecting on partnerships  

642
01:07:14,440 --> 01:07:18,120
that would be much more long-term valuable.
If you're talking about long timeframes, like  

643
01:07:18,120 --> 01:07:23,880
100 years, there is no question. But clearly, the 
correct way to play iterated prisoner's dilemma is  

644
01:07:23,880 --> 01:07:28,840
coordinate for both sides. It's way more valuable 
[inaudible 01:07:27] doing that over long periods  

645
01:07:28,840 --> 01:07:41,480
of time than any momentary defection could 
possibly be convenient at a moment. It's a huge  

646
01:07:41,480 --> 01:07:47,880
amount of product decisions. When we are deciding 
roadmap, end up being very influenced by this,  

647
01:07:47,880 --> 01:07:55,440
because I get pitches for things we should do and 
why don't we do this kind of change to the system,  

648
01:07:56,720 --> 01:08:00,600
there's so much money in it, and all 
these kind of things. I'm like, cool,  

649
01:08:00,600 --> 01:08:06,560
but almost always come in a form of putting 
future profits forward at a discount. 

650
01:08:08,240 --> 01:08:13,760
But we have a long time horizon. Let's not take 
the discount, let's... Also, you often compromise  

651
01:08:13,760 --> 01:08:22,280
the entire business after a while because you 
end up just... Your customers notice if you're  

652
01:08:22,280 --> 01:08:31,600
going into value extraction. The best companies, I 
believe, at least from a perspective of a leader,  

653
01:08:31,600 --> 01:08:39,800
resemble some kind of cockpit, or maybe a room 
full of dials or levers for monetization. My job  

654
01:08:39,800 --> 01:08:44,840
is adding as many of these levers as possible 
to the room, and then not pulling any of them.  

655
01:08:44,840 --> 01:08:52,160
Because I think we do best if we are on the same 
side of a table of our customers and we had them  

656
01:08:52,160 --> 01:08:56,000
become entrepreneurs, which is a mission, and we 
want to support them to be more successful, which  

657
01:08:56,000 --> 01:09:03,280
is the business model we are in. We get a very, 
very small stake of the sales in our monetization  

658
01:09:03,280 --> 01:09:08,600
system. And therefore, we are incentivized 
to make everyone as successful as possible. 

659
01:09:11,440 --> 01:09:16,840
Again, when I get a PowerPoint from investment 
bankers or so, where they tell me I have enormous  

660
01:09:16,840 --> 01:09:23,400
pricing power and I could massively change the 
prices, I'm like, "Yeah, but I'd leave Shopify  

661
01:09:23,400 --> 01:09:30,080
if that happens to me, so how is that good?" 
He's just like, "Why?" It just goes like that.

662
01:09:30,080 --> 01:09:32,720
There's a quote that you wrote somewhere that,  

663
01:09:32,720 --> 01:09:38,080
to me, identifies this point so 
succinctly, "On a long enough timeline,  

664
01:09:38,080 --> 01:09:45,080
playing positive-sum games with your customers 
is the ultimate growth hack." Yeah, beautiful.

665
01:09:46,600 --> 01:09:52,520
I think that's pretty piffy and it's 
also just... Try to argue with it.

666
01:09:52,520 --> 01:09:54,200
That's true.

667
01:09:54,200 --> 01:09:59,720
Positive-sum games have incredible returns, 
especially in the worlds of software,  

668
01:09:59,720 --> 01:10:12,240
where you can experience exponentials very 
easily. I see company building as... I  

669
01:10:12,240 --> 01:10:16,200
wish there would be better analogy than chess, 
because chess is a game of perfect information,  

670
01:10:16,200 --> 01:10:21,720
which is totally incorrect. But one thing which 
I like about chess as an analogy for business is  

671
01:10:21,720 --> 01:10:28,720
that it basically is two games, that you have to 
be good at at both. There's a positional game that  

672
01:10:28,720 --> 01:10:36,360
you learn: Develop your pieces, gain influence 
by your pieces over the board. That's really,  

673
01:10:36,360 --> 01:10:42,120
really important. And then there's tactics, which 
you learn tactic training. You go get a puzzle  

674
01:10:42,120 --> 01:10:51,200
trainer and you drill tactics and you learn the 
intuition to sports tactics, sense them. Both of  

675
01:10:51,200 --> 01:10:55,400
them are actually super independent of each other.
The business world only talks about tactics.  

676
01:10:55,400 --> 01:11:02,560
It only talks about the conversion of we did this 
thing. We did an A/B test and we changed the color  

677
01:11:02,560 --> 01:11:14,160
of blue, and conversion red went up. We lionize 
the easy hack. I don't think that's important,  

678
01:11:14,920 --> 01:11:24,080
honestly. You need to be good enough at tactics to 
not go out of business. You can't get margin code,  

679
01:11:24,080 --> 01:11:29,480
sure. But the sum total of all the 
value of a potential tactics that you  

680
01:11:29,480 --> 01:11:36,000
could employ stays with you if you are 
actually are doing the positional game. 

681
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:43,040
The positional game is like, what is the territory 
on the map that you are taking? What role do you  

682
01:11:43,040 --> 01:11:48,920
play? How much trust do you have of merchants? Do 
merchants want more from you or less? Are you the  

683
01:11:48,920 --> 01:11:55,440
kind of thing they're trying to optimize out of 
their software spend, or the one that they ask to  

684
01:11:55,440 --> 01:12:02,760
subsume all other software spend? Do they rely on 
you? Are you part of a team, or are you used as a  

685
01:12:03,360 --> 01:12:10,360
tool in the toolbox, usually forgotten, sometimes 
coming out when certain task is being done? What  

686
01:12:10,920 --> 01:12:16,680
does your product cover? What industries are you 
addressing? And so on, so on, so on. This is the  

687
01:12:16,680 --> 01:12:22,960
positional game. How well do pieces fit together? 
Do people like relying even deeper on you? 

688
01:12:25,280 --> 01:12:30,280
If you do that well, the tactics are yours 
and you can hire a lot of people who are  

689
01:12:30,280 --> 01:12:35,000
extraordinarily good at spotting tactics 
and using them. But if you do it too much,  

690
01:12:35,000 --> 01:12:42,760
you end up extracting through tactics the 
entirety of the value that you have created  

691
01:12:42,760 --> 01:12:49,880
and that is yours to take through a positional 
game. And if you do that, you have nothing left  

692
01:12:49,880 --> 01:12:54,680
in the tank. That's for companies that we all 
see, that just got to a point and then just  

693
01:12:56,000 --> 01:13:01,960
fade. Those are the companies that 
got tacticked out of their position.

694
01:13:01,960 --> 01:13:05,960
The skill, obviously, is finding the balance 
between these two things of short-term,  

695
01:13:05,960 --> 01:13:09,000
not get margin calls, as you 
described, but also think ahead. 

696
01:13:09,000 --> 01:13:12,080
Is there any kind of heuristic for 
founders listening to this who are like,  

697
01:13:12,800 --> 01:13:15,440
"How do I do this? How much should I be 
thinking about the future versus now?",  

698
01:13:15,440 --> 01:13:19,240
I guess? How do you try to create this 
pie chart of driving goals immediately  

699
01:13:19,240 --> 01:13:22,254
and show investors we're killing 
it, while also thinking ahead?

700
01:13:22,253 --> 01:13:27,800
Is there a good heuristic? Objective number one 
is: Don't die. Again, in the end, for companies  

701
01:13:27,800 --> 01:13:34,520
that become historic companies are the ones 
which did not die. It also sounds very basic,  

702
01:13:34,520 --> 01:13:42,000
but actually it's more actionable than it 
might seem. Past that point, I would argue:  

703
01:13:42,000 --> 01:13:49,840
Just focus on the positional game. I think this 
is where a bit of a discrepancy of the founder and  

704
01:13:49,840 --> 01:14:01,200
the rest of the company sometimes lies. I think 
the founders create finite, winnable games for  

705
01:14:01,200 --> 01:14:09,640
people, that are very much serving the infinite 
game of developing, that the mission implies,  

706
01:14:12,160 --> 01:14:17,280
the quality of position on the board.
By the way, it's an infinite board. Just  

707
01:14:17,280 --> 01:14:21,280
picture the chess board as the initial 
terrain, but there's, I don't know,  

708
01:14:21,280 --> 01:14:26,880
fog on the board and it's a terrain that's much 
larger that you will explore over time. I think  

709
01:14:26,880 --> 01:14:33,560
that's the most prettiest way of mentally thinking 
about the experience of building a company. It's  

710
01:14:33,560 --> 01:14:42,000
an exploration and a collaborative inquiry into a 
question that is implied by the mission. And you  

711
01:14:42,000 --> 01:14:49,800
will get to explore how correct your mission 
is and how good your decision making is along  

712
01:14:49,800 --> 01:14:54,760
the way. And you get to learn a lot, and this 
is why I think it's a valuable thing to do. 

713
01:14:54,760 --> 01:15:03,920
But they often, the founders, and the mission 
of a company are in alignment, but they are,  

714
01:15:03,920 --> 01:15:12,960
again, non-quantifiable things. They are 
pursuits. Maybe as time horizons that go past,  

715
01:15:12,960 --> 01:15:19,480
all of our time horizons of our careers, therefore 
that makes it hard for people to care deeply yet.  

716
01:15:19,480 --> 01:15:24,320
But they do care about the instances, the games 
along the way, the [inaudible 01:15:24] that have  

717
01:15:24,320 --> 01:15:29,560
to be done to explore a part of a map, 
the tactics that have to be executed.

718
01:15:29,560 --> 01:15:33,040
I'm not going to take us here, but I know you're a 
big fan of this book, Finite and Infinite Games. I  

719
01:15:33,040 --> 01:15:37,560
actually had it once at a book club and it blew my 
mind open. I'm going to link to it. People should  

720
01:15:37,560 --> 01:15:40,200
check it out. You've talked about this on another 
podcast. I'm not going to [inaudible 01:15:40].

721
01:15:40,200 --> 01:15:45,120
Yeah, it's a lovely book. James Carse did 
